[[File:Alcatraz yard.jpg|thumb|Alcatraz recreation yard]] The '''Recreation Yard''' was the yard used by inmates of [[Alcatraz Federal Penitentiary]] between 1934 and 1963. It is located opposite the [[Alcatraz Dining Hall|Dining Hall]] south of the end of D-Block on a raised level surrounded by a high wall and fence above it.<ref name="Historic Preservation">{{cite book|title=Historic Preservation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=C4RXnwuKT-MC|accessdate=31 August 2012|year=1995|page=91}}</ref><ref name="EagleAssociation1992"/> Guard Tower #3 lay just to the west of the yard.<ref name="Dunbar1999">{{cite book|last=Dunbar|first=Richard|title=Alcatraz|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OoXM5O9glN8C&pg=PA71|accessdate=31 August 2012|date=1 January 1999|publisher=Casa Editrice Bonechi|isbn=978-88-8029-940-0|page=71}}</ref> The gun gallery was situated in the yard, mounted on one of the dining hall's exterior walls.<ref name="Champion2012">{{cite book|last=Champion Jr.|first=Jerry Lewis |title=Alcatraz Unchained|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VQV5wM6qj1oC&pg=PA140|accessdate=2 September 2012|date=26 April 2012|publisher=AuthorHouse|isbn=978-1-4685-8753-1|pages=140–}}</ref> The recreation yard faced the mainland.<ref name="Moseley2009">{{cite book|last=Moseley|first=Andy|title=Around the States in 90 Days|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JrGH3ZuNggIC&pg=PA268|accessdate=2 September 2012|date=September 2009|publisher=andy moseley|isbn=978-0-9561551-0-8|pages=268–}}</ref>
==History== In 1936, the previously dirt-covered yard was paved.<ref name="WardKassebaum2009">{{cite book|last1=Ward|first1=David A.|last2=Kassebaum|first2=Gene G.|title=Alcatraz: The Gangster Years|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kV6KXrkQjTsC&pg=PA47|accessdate=2 September 2012|date=19 May 2009|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=978-0-520-25607-1|pages=47–}}</ref> The yard was part of the most violent escape attempt from Alcatraz in May 1946 when a group of inmates hatched a plot to obtain the key into the recreation yard, kill the tower guards, take hostages, and use them as shields to reach the dock.<ref name="Watson2012">{{cite book|last=Watson|first=Stephanie|title=The Escape from Alcatraz|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dw-4z4Cmb8MC&pg=PA47|accessdate=31 August 2012|date=1 January 2012|publisher=ABDO|isbn=978-1-61783-303-8|page=47}}</ref> During the [[Occupation of Alcatraz]] in 1970, between 400 and 700 Native Indians assembled in the recreation yard and demonstrated.<ref name="EagleAssociation1992">{{cite book|first1=Adam |last1=Fortunate Eagle|author2=Golden Gate National Park Association|title=Alcatraz! Alcatraz!: the Indian occupation of 1969-1971|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zbRgon2K0QEC|accessdate=31 August 2012|year=1992|publisher=Heyday Books|isbn=978-0-930588-51-9|page=84}}</ref>
==Terms== [[File:The Yard in Alcatraz.jpg|thumb|left]] Inmates were permitted out into the yard on Saturdays, Sundays and on holidays for a maximum of 5 hours.<ref name="Wellman2008">{{cite book|last=Wellman|first=Gregory L.|title=A History of Alcatraz Island:: 1853-2008|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1duAUPaHSgcC&pg=PA51|accessdate=31 August 2012|date=28 May 2008|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|isbn=978-0-7385-5815-8|page=51}}</ref><ref name="Albright2008">{{cite book|last=Albright|first=Jim|title=Last Guard Out: A Riveting Account by the Last Guard to Leave Alcatraz|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fmVGYLGkLl4C&pg=PA151|accessdate=31 August 2012|date=30 March 2008|publisher=AuthorHouse|isbn=978-1-4343-5077-0|page=151}}</ref> Inmates who worked seven days a week in the kitchen were rewarded with short yard breaks during the weekdays.<ref name="Albright2008"/> Badly behaved prisoners were liable to having their yard access rights taken away from them on weekends.<ref name="Albright2008"/>
==Social interaction== [[File:Alcatraz aerial.jpg|thumb|right|Aerial view showing the main cellblock, dining hall area, and the yard in front of it and just to the right.]] [[File:Alcatraz yard1.jpg|thumb|right|View of the [[Alcatraz Water Tower|water tower]] from the yard]] [[File:Alcatraz yard2.jpg|thumb|right|Looking through the fence into the yard]] The prisoners of Alcatraz were permitted to play games such as [[baseball]], [[softball]] and other sports at these times, and intellectual games such as [[chess]].<ref name="Wellman2008"/> Basketball also appears to have been played on the yard judging by the markings which are still visible on the yard today. Baseball and softball were the most popular. Because of the small size of the yard and the [[baseball field|diamond]] at the end of it, a section of the wall behind the first base had to be padded to cushion the impact of inmates overrunning it.<ref name="Seymour1991">{{cite book|last=Seymour|first=Harold|title=Baseball: The People's Game|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oJuwTnbkmUMC&pg=PA431|accessdate=31 August 2012|date=30 May 1991|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-506907-5|page=431}}</ref> Inmates were provided [[baseball glove|gloves]], [[baseball bat|bats]], and [[Baseball (ball)|balls]], but no [[baseball uniform|sport uniforms]]. In 1938, there were four amateur teams, the Bees, Oaks, Oilers, and Seals, named after [[Minor League Baseball|Minor League]] clubs, and four league teams named after [[Major League Baseball|Major League]] clubs, the Cardinals, Cubs, Giants, and Tigers.<ref name="NPS">{{cite web|url=http://www.nps.gov/alca/historyculture/baseball-on-the-rock.htm|title=For it's one, two, three strikes, you're (not) out, at the old ball game.'|publisher=National Park Service|accessdate=31 August 2012}}</ref> Bank robber and kidnapper [[Volney Davis]] was a pitching ace for the Oilers, while [[Lorenzo Murrietta]], doing 40 years for assault and robbery, was the best batter in Alcatraz league play. He had a .402 [[batting average]], with 9 [[home run]]s and 45 [[Run batted in|RBIs]] for the Cardinals.<ref name="NPS"/> Although many of the inmates relished the opportunity to exercise on weekends, violence occasionally occurred, often race related. A notable riot occurred on May 20, 1956 over racial taunts on the diamond between a white and black prisoner during a softball match.<ref name="NPS"/> [[File:Alcatraz yard3.jpg|thumb|left|View from the diamond]] Many of the inmates used weekends in the yards to converse with each other and discuss crime, the only real opportunities they had during the week for active conversation.<ref name="Jr2011">{{cite book|first=Jerry Lewis |last=Champion Jr|title=The Fading Voices of Alcatraz|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GxH3-mB5rCcC&pg=PA119|accessdate=31 August 2012|date=27 January 2011|publisher=AuthorHouse|isbn=978-1-4567-1488-8|page=119}}</ref> [[Machine Gun Kelly]] and [[Basil Banghart|Basil "The Owl" Banghart]] were said to be inseparable in the yard and would spend their whole time walking around it in conversation together.<ref name="Jr2011"/> [[Al Capone]], on the other hand, avoided the yard in his later years in the penitentiary as his mind deteriorated.<ref name="Sloate2008">{{cite book|last=Sloate|first=Susan|title=Mysteries Unwrapped: The Secrets of Alcatraz|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0yUpfWv68aYC&pg=PA83|accessdate=31 August 2012|date=1 April 2008|publisher=Sterling Publishing Company, Inc.|isbn=978-1-4027-3591-2|page=83}}</ref> [[Edwin B. Swope]], Warden of Alcatraz from 1948 to 1955, once said, in response to an inmate who complained to him on the yard about his term of 199 years, which was really a life sentence, "My boy, we're all doing life. Every one of us is doing life."<ref name="Jr2011"/>
==In popular culture== The Alcatraz recreation yard has been a setting for scenes in numerous films and novels. Scenes have featured prison inmates hatching schemes or being involved in bloody conflicts. The yard featured several times in the 1979 [[Clint Eastwood]] film ''[[Escape from Alcatraz (film)|Escape from Alcatraz]]'' including a violent fight; it was parodied in the 1994 [[Leslie Nielsen]] film, ''[[Naked Gun 33⅓: The Final Insult]]''.
